==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Keelson
<hw>Keel"son</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Akin to Sw.
<ets>k⟦oum⟧lsvin</ets>, Dan. <ets>kj⟦oum⟧lsviin</ets>, G.
<ets>kielschwein</ets>; apparently compounded of the words
<ets>keel</ets> and <ets>swine</ets>; but cf. Norweg.
<ets>kj⟦oum⟧lsvill</ets>, where <ets>svill</ets> is akin to E.
<ets>sill</ets>, <pos>n.</pos> ]</ety> <fld>(Shipbuilding)</fld> <def>A
piece of timber in a ship laid on the middle of the floor timbers over
the keel, and binding the floor timbers to the keel; in iron vessels, a
structure of plates, situated like the keelson of a timber
ship.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Cross keelson</b></col>, <cd>a similar structure lying
athwart the main keelson, to support the engines and
boilers.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 810 --></p>

<p><ent>Keelvat</ent>⟦br⟧
